<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is an IBU?", answer: "IBU stands for International Bitterness Unit and measures the concentration of iso-alpha acids in beer in parts per million. One IBU equals one milligram of iso-alpha acid per liter of beer. IBUs are the standard objective measure of beer bitterness, although perceived bitterness also depends on residual sweetness, alcohol, water mineral content, and yeast character." },
  { question: "What is the Tinseth formula?", answer: "The Tinseth formula was developed by homebrewer Glenn Tinseth in 1997 to predict iso-alpha acid utilization during the boil. It accounts for the gravity of the wort and the boil time of each hop addition: utilization equals 1.65 times 0.000125 raised to the power of OG minus 1, multiplied by 1 minus e to the negative 0.04 times boil time, all divided by 4.15. Tinseth is the most popular IBU model among homebrewers because it matches commercial beer measurements reasonably well." },
  { question: "How many IBUs should my beer have?", answer: "It depends on the style. Light lagers and witbiers usually sit between 8 and 18 IBU, pale ales 30 to 45, English IPAs 40 to 55, American IPAs 50 to 75, and double IPAs 65 to 100. Stouts and porters can range widely from 25 to 60 depending on whether they balance heavy roast and chocolate flavors. The official BJCP Style Guidelines list target IBU ranges for every recognized style." },
  { question: "Does dry hopping add IBUs?", answer: "Practically no measurable IBUs come from dry hopping. Dry hops are added after the boil, so the alpha acids are not isomerized and contribute almost no measurable bitterness in lab IBU tests. Dry hopping does add hop flavor and aroma, and can sometimes contribute a perception of dryness or bitterness through hop oils and polyphenols, but those compounds are not measured by the standard IBU spectrophotometric test." },
  { question: "Why does higher gravity wort produce fewer IBUs?", answer: "At higher original gravities, dissolved sugars reduce the solubility of iso-alpha acids and lower their utilization. The Tinseth bigness factor accounts for this with the term 1.65 times 0.000125 raised to OG minus 1. A 1.080 wort gives roughly 22 percent fewer IBUs from the same hop addition than a 1.040 wort, which is why imperial IPAs require so much more hops than session IPAs to taste similarly bitter." }
]) %>

